  "text": "In contrast, several studies have reported inflammatory disease after major trauma with early definitive treatment. In one study, 38% of trauma patients who underwent major secondary reconstructive surgery (ie, facial reconstruction; osteosynthesis of the pelvic girdle, long bones, or spine) within 3 days after admission developed MOFS. [CITATION_1] Patients who developed MOFS had significantly higher preoperative levels of PMN elastase-α1 proteinase inhibitor complex and CRP than did those who did not develop MOFS. The authors concluded that the initial degree of inflammatory system priming was a major factor in the subsequent development of MOFS after surgery. Another clinical study reported a fourfold increase in the incidence of ARDS in patients with chest injury who underwent definitive femoral fracture fixation within 24 hours of admission compared with patients who underwent fracture repair any time after the first day of admission. [CITATION_2] Ideally, advancing the ability to analyze immunoinflammatory molecular markers will improve our understanding of the appropriate timing for surgical intervention in high-risk patients.",
